{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514154430/1948082101/0323.xml":{"full_text":"SATURDAY\n1 P.N. Edition\nTHE\nALASKA EMPIRE\nSATURDAr\nI P.N. Edition\n\"ALL THE NEWS ALL THE TIMET\u2019\nVOL. LXVIII., NO. 10,971\nJUNEAU, ALASKA, SATURDAY, AUGUST 21, 1948\nMEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nPRICE TEN CENTS\nCharges Are Filed Against Longshoremen\nSOVIETS\nKIDNAP\nPOLICE\nBERLIN, Aug. 21.\u2014Iff)\u2014Russian\nsoldiers kidnaped four more West\nern sector German policemen today\n\u2014two with violence\u2014in a continu\nation of raids which Americans\nfear may grow into a serious in\nternational incident.\nThe Soviet forces struck again\nafter the Americans had announced\nthey would seek face-to-face talks\nwith the Russians to try for a\ntruce in the conflict involving\nBerlin's divided police force.\nHeadquarters of the Western\nsector police announced a large\nparty of Russian soldiers halted\ntwo German plain clothes men\nfrom the American Zone near the\nsector border, stabbed one, beat\nthe other with a rifle butt, and\ncarried them into the Soviet Zone\nbodily when they refused to cross\nthe line.\nTwo German policemen of the\nBritish sector were the others kid\nnaped. One escaped and the Brit\nish are demanding return of the\nsecond.\nThe Russians yesterday seized\nfive policemen from the Ameri\ncan Zone. Two of them have es\ncaped. The Americans have asked\nreturn of the others but receive*\nno reply. Thus, of the nine police?\u2019\nmen taken, the Russians stfll ^ol*\nsix.\nTension mounted hourly in this\ndivided four-power city. Russian\nsoldiers, tommyguns at ready, pa\ntrolled their side of the sector\nborder. A short distance away,\nunder the Russians\u2019 cold stares,\nBritish and American patrols were\non the alert.\nWestern sector police have ord\nered motorized reserves to stand\nby, ready to speed to the boundar\nies at a sign of trouble.\nThe Russians have made a series\nof lightning raids into the Western\nsectors, ostensibly against black\nmarketeers.\nSITKAN HERE\nSgt. Harry Wallace of Sitka is|\nstaying at the Gastineau Hotel.\nFROM WISCONSIN\nArthur C. Lewis of Racine, Wis.,\nis a guest at the Baranof Hotel.\nThe Washington\nMerry-Go-Round\nBY ROBERT 6. ALLEN\nicoprrlfht. 1948, br The Ml Srndtcato.\nInc.)\n(Editor\u2019s Note While Drew\nPearson is on a brief vacation\nThe Washington Merry-Go\nRound is being written by his\nold partner, Robert 8. Allen.)\nWashington Rpbert r.\nYoung, scrappy head of the Chesa\npeake St Ohio Railroad, is return\ning to the wars.\nIn an exclusive interview with\nthe Washington Merry-Go-Round,\nthe truculent little Texan announc\ned his intention to make a new\nfight to gain control of the New\nYork Central system, took a lusty\npoke at the Association of Ameri\ncan Railroads, blasted both Demo\ncrats and Republicans, and de\nnounced pouring taxpayers\u2019 money\n\u201cdown the vast China rathole.\"\nYoung was tripped up on his\nplan to become the leading railroad\ntycoon of the country when the\nInterstate Commerce Commission,\nlast spring, blocked his taking over\nthe New York Central.\nThe ICC held the consolidation\nwould be harmful to the Virgin\nian Railway. This carrier, a com\npetitor of Young\u2019s C. Se O., has\nlarge contracts with the New York\nCentral. Young now has it all\nfigured out how to meet this ICC\nobjection.\nHe proposes to take over the\nVirginian.\n\u201cWe will refile our application\nwith the ICC,\u201d he said, \u201cand in\nclude the Virginian in our plans.\n(Continued on Page Four)\nI\nSOVIET CONSUL\nBOOKS PASSAGE\nFOR TRIP HOME\nNEW YORK, Aug. 21\u2014OB\u2014Soviet\nConsul Jacob M. Lomakin, whom the\nState Department has expelled, has\nbooked passage aboard the Swedish\nAmerican liner Stockholm, sailing\nnext Saturday.\nThe steamship line said that\nLomakin had made reservations lor\nhimselt and his wife and two\nchildren. It said it could not dis\nclose when the discredited envoy\nhad booked his passage.\nA line spokesman said, however:\n\"We have no record of the book\ning here. It was done in Europe.\u201d\nThe Stockholm plies between New\nYork and Gothenburg. Lomakin's\nreturn to Moscow presumably will\nbe made via Finland.\nLomakin, accused by the U. S. of\nmisrepresenting the facts in the case\nof Mrs. Oksana Kasenkina, has re\nfused to comment on the U. S. de\nmand to the Soviet Embassy in\nWashington that he be recalled to\nRussia.\nLomakin had claimed he \u201crescued\u201d\nMre. Kasenkina from an anti-Com\njnunist farm retreat, operated by\nCounteas Alexander Tolstoy.\nAfter the teacher's leap from the\nConsulate window, however, police\nquoted her as saying she had been\nheld a prisoner.\nConsulate officials however,\nclaimed she was trying to commit\nmicide and was under great ner\ntous tension because of the actions\nOf the White Russian antl-Onn\nBiunlsts and American lifTVtals.\nThe U. S. demand for Lomakin's\nouster was the latest in a series\nof charges and countercharges In\nthe case between Washington and\nMoscow.\nMeanwhile, Dr. Grant Pennoyer,\nhospital resident physician, said\nMrs. Kasenkina, who suffered multi\nfractures and internal injuries In\nher plunge, is \u2018improving right\nalong.\u2019\u2019\nMOSCOW, Aug. 21 \u2014(^1\u2014Soviet\npapers have not yet carried the\nnews that the U. S. State Depart\nment has asked for the recall of\nthe Soviet Consul General in New|\nYork, Jacob M. Lomakin.\nNAVY SHIP IS DUE\nIN SEATTLE WITH\nPRIBILOF CARGO\nSEATTLE, Aug. 21. (*1 The\nNavy cargo ship Thuban is due in\nSeattle today with a $4,000,000 load\nof seal skins and by-products from\nthe annual sealing expedition to\nthe Pribilof Islands north of the\nAleutians.\nSeal skins will go to St. Louis for\nauctioning. The proceeds, under an\ninternational agreement for con\ntroled sealing operations, will go to\nRussia, Canada and the United\nStates.\nSOUTH 10 SUPPORT\nHOVE FOR POPULAR\nPRESIDENTIAL VOTE\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21\u2014l/h\u2014\nSouthern Democratic support ap\npeared today for a move by Sena\ntor Lodge (R-Mass) to put presi\ndential elections on a popular vote\nbasis.\nSenators Sparkman (D-Ala) and\nOlin D. Johnston (D-SC) told a\nreporter in separate interviews they\nwill back in the next session of\nCongress a proposal to change the\npresent system by which a state\u2019s\nentire electoral college vote is cast j\nfor the candidate who tops the\npopular ballot test.\nLodge offered in the last session\nand intends to revive a proposed\nconstitutional amendment under!\nwhich each candidate would share\nin the electoral vote on the precent\nage of his election day total.\nThus an aspirant who lost out by\nonly a few popular votes to his\npresidential opponent would get\nnearly half of the state's support\nin the electoral college, instead of\nnone at all.\nSparkman said he thinks Southern\nDemocrats generally will support the\nproposal because it would \u201cgo a long\nway .toward doing away with minor\nity rule in this country.\"\nSubpoena\nReady for\nHigh Red\nWASHINGTON, Q. C., Aug. 21.\u2014\noft\u2014A House committee subpoena\nwill be ready today for J. Peters,\nthe man named as the head of the\npre-war Communist underground\nin this country. Right now, Peters\nis out on bail while awaiting a de\nportation hearing, and it is not\nknown just where he is.\nBut Immigration Commissioner\nWatsorr Miller has promised an\nearly hearing in the deportation\ncase, and then the House Un-Ameri\ncan Activities Committee will be\nable to tag Peters with its subpoena.\nOf course, even when the com\nmittee does get hold of Peters, it\nmay not learn very much about the\nCommunist underground. Peters\nmay refuse to talk, just as several\nother witnesses have done. However,\ncommittee members point out that\nPeters might be willing to name\nnames in exchange for immunity\n[from deportation.\nDistrict Attorney\nConducts Gambling\nRaid at Anchorage\nANCHORAGE, Aug. 21\u2014Former\nAnchorage City Council candidate\nWalter B. Orr was arrested early\nyesterday morning and charged\nwith maintaining and operating a\ngambling house here. He was re\nleased on $1,000 bail. The arrest\nwas made by a party of leading law\nenforcement officials Including the\nDistrict Attorney, Deputy U. S.\nMarshal, Chief oi Police and a Police\nCaptain.\nPROTEST HIGH TAX\nON TOBACCO, PACK\nOF CIGARETTES 70c\nLONDON, Aug. 21.\u2014UH\u2014A trade\nunion leader threatened the Labor\nGovernment today with a \"revolt\u201d\nunless taxes on cigarettes and beer\nare cut.\n\"It should be clearly understood,\u201d\nsaid General Secretary E. J. Hill\nin his monthly report to the Boiler\nmakers\u2019 Union, \"that the workers\nin heavy industry do not intend to\ngive up beer drinking and smok\ning and the sooner the tax on\nthem is reduced the better. Other\nwise they will revolt, and their\nprofound loyalty to the Labor Gov\nernment will turn to hostility.\u201d\nThe Government increased the\ntobacco tax drastically last spring\nin an effort to compel a reduction\nin consumption which would save\ndollars for other imports,., A cig\narette shortage has resulted. The\nprice has risen to 70 cents for a\npackage of 20.\nPrincess Margaret Is\n18 Years Old Today\nLONDON, Aug. 21.\u2014Wl\u2014Princess\nMargaret, officially of age, aban\ndons her role of little sister today.\nIt is her eighteenth birthday\nand a solemn occasion for the\nmerry Princess whose wit and nat\nuralness have endeared her to the\nentire commonwealth.\nAll her life, Princess Margaret\nhas been overshadowed by her old\ner sister Elizabeth, the heiress pre\nsumptive to the throne of Britain.\nBut now Elizabeth, expecting her\nfirst child in the fall, has virtual\nly discontinued public appearances,\nand it falls to Margaret to should\ner some of the duties of state.\nActually, Margaret's coming of\nage in this case means only that\nin the event of her succession to\nthe throne she could rule without\na regent and that her \"social re\nsponsibilities henceforth will be\ngreater. Otherwise, however, she\nremains a minor until she is 21.\nJOINT CHIEFS OF\nSTAFF HOLDING\nSECRET MEETING\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21.\u2014A\nclosed-tight gathering ol U. S.\nJoint Chiefs of Staffs worked in\nthe quiet of the Naval War College\nat Newport, R. I\u201e this weekend on\nmilitary defense secrets.\nMeeting with Secretary of De\nfense Forrestal, the nation\u2019s war\nchiefs were billed to take up a\nbroad study of weapons and con\nsider problems of strategic air\nwarfare.\nGen. Hoyt Vandenberg, Air Force\nChief of Staff, was there fresh\nfrom observing the Berlin air lift.\nForrestal was prepared to report\non his talks last week with Can\nadian defense chiefs.\nSuch meetings will be held every\nfew months, the Defense Depart\nment said, away from the pressure\nand interruptions of official Wash\nington.\nAIR FORCE MAN\nDROWNS, AUG. 15\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21\u2014OB\u2014\nThe U. S. Air Force said yesterday\nj that Cpl. Herbert Lee Linville, son\nI of Mr. and Mrs. O. M. Linville, Val\nI rico, Fla. was drowned in Alaska\nIon August 15. No other details were\nI immediately available. His parents\n(have been notified.\nicONSIDER NAMES\nAT GLACIER BAY\nBy VERN HAUGHLAND\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21\u2014(API\u2014An\ninlet created by the gradual melt\ning of an Alaskan glacier may be\nnamed for the University of Wiscon\nsin.\nIt is one of 32 places in Glacier\nBay National Monument, Southeast\nAlaska, under study by the U. S.\n(Board on geographic names.\nJ The National Park Service is pre\ni paring a new map of the area, and\nhas asked the Board to designate\nI officially the names for various fea\ntures, Including those created by\nthe year-to-year recession of the\nglaciers.\nMany of the names proposed are\nconnected with early expeditions in\nto Alaska.\nI The feature which has been shown\nion sonfe maps as Cushing Inlet\nI would be named Wisconsin Inlet, in\none proposal before the Board, be\ncause of the many University of\nWisconsin scientists who have\nstudied the Glacier Bay area. The\n(inlet was formed in recent years\n|by the recession of Plateau Glacier.\nWeekly Salmon\nPack Report\nShows Decrease\nSEATTLE, Ang. 21.\u2014\u2014Alaska's\nsalmon pack totaled 2,745,994 cases\nthrough August 14, compared with\n3,388,897 cases at about the same\ndate last year, the.Federal Fish and\nWlidlife Service reported today.\nThe pack was lower this year in\nall major districts. Figures for Aug.\n14 this year and Aug. 16, 1947;\nWestern Alaska. 1,373,443 and 1,418,\n266; Central Alaska, 1,187,919 and\n1,668,887; ./Southeast Alaska, 195,\n632 and 301,744.\nSTEAMERMOVEMfMTS\nBaranof arriving here south\nbound 4 p. m. Monday.\nSquare Sinnett sailed north from\nSeattle at 8 o\u2019clock Tuesday night.\nCoastal Monarch sailed north\nbound from Seattle Thursday.\nGeorge Washington due north\ni bound at 3 p.m. Monday.\nPrincess Norah arriving north\nbound this afternoon or evening.\nAleutian leaving Seattle today.\nJumper Hitch scheduled to sail\nnorthbound August 26.\nFISH BAY\nI Mrs. Kenny Westfall and Allen\ni Westfall from Fish Bay are visiting\nin Juneau, and staying at the\nI Baranof Hotel.\nI\nBULLETINS\nMOSCOW,\u2014U. S. Ambasador Wal\nter B, Smith, French Ambassador\nYves Chataigneau and Frank Rob\nerts, Special British Envoy, con\nferred at the British Embassy late\ntoday. Sources in the U. S. Em\nbassy Indicated there would be no\nmeeting of the three with Poregin\nMinister V. M. Molotov tonight and\nthat there is- little chance lor a four\npower meeting tomorrow.\nLAKE SUCCESS\u2014A British\nspokesman said today Ills govern\nment can not approve Israel\u2019s ad\nmission to the United Nations un\nder present conditions.\nNEW YORK,\u2014Gen. Jonathan M\nWalnwrigW, hero of Bataan and\nCorregidor, has been elected Na\ntional Commander of the disabled\nAmerican veterans.\nRAPID CITY, S. D.,\u2014Seventeen\nmen died late yesterday when a B\n'20 crashed and burned a few seconds\nalter taking off from a 15th Air\nForce base near here.\nSPOKANE,\u2014A group of B-29 Su\nperfortresses winged toward Okina\nwa today for an extended period\nof over-water training missions\nkfo^e will follow during the weekend.\nRAILROADS AND\nHIGHWAYS NOW\nOK, ANCHORAGE\nANCHORAGE, Aug. 21\u2014Pull land\ncommunication to the rest of the\n[world was restored to Anchorage\nI yesterday after disastrous floods,\n(earlier this week, had washed out\n[highways and railroads.\nPAYMENT DUE ON\nVET INSURANCE,\nREINSTATED, JULY\nAlaskan veterans who reinstated\ntheir G. X. insurance just betore\nthe July 31 \"easy reinstatement\u201d\ndeadline should pay another month\nly premium to the Veterans Admin\nistration Branch No. 11, Exchange\nBldg., Seattle, Wash., Immediately\nto prevent the policy lapsing again,\nthe VA said today.\nMost veterans who reinstated their\nNational Service Life Insurance last\nmonth paid only the required two\nmonths\u2019 premiums, the VA ex\nplained. Under G. I. insurance regu\nlations, one premium covered the 30\nday grace period before the policy\nlapsed and the other the month ot\nreinstatement.\nG. I. Insurance premiums may be\npaid monthly, quarterly, semi-an\nnually or annually. Advance pay\nments, other than monthly, are dis\ncounted by the VA and result in\neven greater economy to the G. I.\npolicy holder.\nFROM, DILLINGHAM\nMrs. Fern Rivers and children\nand Mrs. Muriel Spears and chil\ndren, all ot Dlllihgham, Alaska,\nare stopping at the Gastineau Ho\ntel.\nWEATHER REPORT\n(U. 8. WEATHER BUREAU)\nTemperature for 24-hour period\nending 7:30 this morning.\nIn Juneau\u2014 Maximum, 67;\nminimum, SO.\nAt Airport\u2014 Maximum, 68;\nminimum 43.\nFORECAST\n(Juneau and Vicinity)\nConsiderable high thin\ncloudiness this afternoon\nand Sunday. Highest tem\nperature near 70 degrees to\nday.\nPRECIPITATION\n(Past 24 hours ending 7:30\na. m. today*\nIn Juneau 0 inches;\nsince August 1, 2.77 inches;\nsince July 1, 9.92 inches.\nAt Airport 0 inches;\nsince August 1. 1.89 inches;\nsince Juiy 1, 6.73 inches.\nNLRB Charges ILWU\nViolating Provisions\nOf Tail-Hartley Ad\nDOUGLAS LABOR\nDISPUTE TO BE\nINVESTIGATED\nKen Bowman, AFL International\nRepresentative for Alaska, return*\ned here yesterday afternoon from\n1 Ketchikan in order to investigate\nI the dispute between the AFL Uni\nted Alaska Fishermen and Cannery\nWorkers Union and the Douglas\nCannery.\nBowman said this morning that\nhe is still investigating all angles\nof the dispute and will be unable\nto give a report until his investi\ngation is complete.\nThe union claims that it had\nreached an agreement with the\ncompany but that when the con\ntract was presented for formal sig\nnature, found that the company\nhad already signed up with the CIO\nFood, Tobacco and Agricultural\nI Workers Union.\nPAN AMERICAN\nl PIONEERS NEW\nFLYING METHOD\nThe long way around is sometimes\ni the shortest line between two points.\nThat's what Pan American Air\nways master pilots, navigators and\nweathermen can show practically\nany day In the airline\u2019s trans-Paci\nlie flights.\nIt\u2019s a newly perfected scientific\ni method of navigation called \"pres\nIsure pattern flying,\u201d in which the\nweather men forecast the winds\nI along flight routes in advance and\nthe captains of the planes shop\nI around for favorable currents.\nThe old yankee clipper captains,\nj piloting their rakish craft across the\nPacific in the China tea trade used\nI to seek out the \"prevailing wester\nlies\u201d on their way back.\nAnd so today master pilots of\nPAA Clippers seek out the winds\nthat will help them along their way\nj by boosting the plane\u2019s speed in the\ni desired direction.\nThese favorable air currents make\nan important difference in Pacific\nflight;; where a plane crosses 2,000\nmiles ocean without stopping. They\ncan take\u2019 hours off flight time, de\ncrease gasoline consumption, enable\nj the planes to carry greater loads.\nIn the opposite sense, if the pilots\nI and navigators ot the plane are not\nforewarned, and strike air currents\nblowing them, they are delayed,\nJ use more fuel and decrease the pos\nsible passengers and cargo loads.\nAs he goes along in flight the\nJ pilot\u2019s instruments, altimeters, baro\nmeters and such, show him where\nhe is in relation to the weather\npressure pattern map. He regulates\nhis course accordingly. But since\nI pressure areas are constantly chang\ning, the captain may find that the\nlair currents have changed somewhat\nin the short time since the weather\nreports were Incorporated into his\nmap. He can then figure the possible j\nj path of the currents, shop around in\nthe upper reaches of the air until\nhe finds the winds he wants.\nHe can alsp receive adjusted wea- j\nther reports'by radio while in flight\nthat help him in plotting his course.\nThe resulting course sometimes rep\nresents a deviation of a, couple of\nhundred miles from a straight line.\nPun American Airways pioneered\nthis new and scientific form of air\ncraft navigation. It sounds simple,\nbut it is no game for amateurs,\nthey point out. Only experts can^\nget results in pressure pattern fly\ning. The men who master-mind it\nare not only fliers and navigators,\nthey are weather specialists in ad\ndition.\nThe technique is being steadily\ndeveloped and improved as exper\nI ience and training grow. PAA, al\nj though it is their own development,\nare not selfish about the thing.\nThey are sharing their knowledge ot\nflying with master pilots and navi\ngators of other air lines.\n1\nSAN FRANCISCO, Aug. 21\u2014(Jf*\u2014\nHarry Bridges' CIO Longshoremen\nmust appear before a National La\nbor Relations Board trial examiner\nhere Sept. 1 to answer an NLRB\ncomplaint charging them with vio\nlating the Taft-Hartley Act.\nI The complaint was issued yester\nday by Regional NLRB Director\nI Gerald Brown. It cited the Inter\nnational Longshoremen's and Ware\nhousemen's Union and two affiliated\ngroups with \"refusing to bargain\nin good faith and by insisting upon\na hiring hall arrangement which\nis Illegal.\"\nThe Waterfront. Employers Asso\nciation filed unfair labor practice\ncharges against the ILWU last June\n10, a few days before a scheduled\ntoastwide strike by five maritime\nunions.\nThe strike was averted by a feder\nal court injunction which expires\nSept. 2. A second injunction to ex\ntend the strike ban could result\nfrom the Sept. 1 hearing\nThe employers, in a stand upheld\nby the NLRB this week, have main\ntained that hiring hjdls in which\ndispatchers are union members are\nillegal under the Taft-Hartley Act.\nThey have insisted on \u201cimpartial\nthird parties\" lor dispatchers.\nThe controversy has been the\nprincipal Issue in the deadlock over\nnew contract Nr*nepJ*ee Hie one\nwhich expired June IS. But last\nnight a coastwide caucus of the IL\nWU declared settlement of the hir\ning hall Issue would ntfc settle the\nprojected Sept. 2 strike.\nThe caucus rejected a \u201cUnal off\ner\" by the WEA which included a\nfive percent wage increase.\nWest Coast employers have de\nclined to loilow the lead of At\nlantic and Gulf Coast shipowners\nwho have agreed to continue a\nunion dispatcher hiring hall ar\nrangement with the National Mari\ntime Union unless the Supreme\nCourt rules it Illegal.\nEAST COAST INJUNCTION\nNEW YORK, Aug. 21\u2014<A5\u2014The'\nFederal Government today obtained\na temporary injunction barring a\nstrike of 45,000 East Coast dock\nworkers set for midnight tonight.\nFederal Judge Harold R. Medina\nissued against the AFL Interna\ntional Longshoremen's Association.\nIt will be effective until Aug. 31.\nALBERT FISK, FORMER\nJUNEAU MAN, KILLED\nIN MINING ACCIDENT\nAlbert L. Fisk. 40, former Juneau\nresident, was fatally injured in a\nmine accident at Republic, \u00bbWash,\nWednesday, according to a wire re\nceived here by William H. Biggs,\nSecretary of the Elks Lodge, from\nFisk\u2019s brother, Roger L. Fisk.\nFuneral services will be held Mon\nday at Valley, Wash. Mr. Fisk, be\nlieved to have been an employee\nof the Alaska Juneau Mine many\nveers ago, had been a member of\nJuneau Lodge No. 420, B. P. O. Elks\nsince 1931. He was born December\n31. 1908. in Valley, Wash.\nGreek Amy Reported\nGaining Against Reds\nATHENS. Aug. 21\u2014W\u2014Uncon\nfirmed press reports said the Greek\nArmy today closed giant armed\npinchers in the Grammos Mountain\nsector cutting the Communists\nforces in two.\nThe General Staff could not con\nfirm the report but said the long\nawaited juncture of two Greek\narmies in that area was possible.\nCasualty figures indicated the\nGreek Army is paying a high price\nfor victory as their armies roll on.\nA communique said 22 men were\nkilled and 148 wounded in the Nes\ntorian sector alone yesterday. It said\n57 dead guerrillas were counted.\nFROM ILLINOIS\nA visitor from OTallon, 111.. Em\nert Jarvis is staying at the Baranof\nHotel.\nNEW CLOSING\nBRINGS MORE\nOBJECTIONS\nDelegation Coming Here\nto Protest-Day Is\nCriticized\nj Albert M. Day, Director, Pish and\nWUdliie Service, announced this\nafternoon that the Eastern Dis\njtrict. Sumner Strait District, and\nthe northern, central and south\nwest sections of the Clarence Strait\nDistrict would be closed to commer\ncial fishing for salmon, except by\ntrolling, in the period lrom 6:00 a.m.\nAugust 23 to 6:00 am. August 27.\nThe closure will not apply to the use\nof glllnets in Taku Inlet and Port\nSnettlsham.\nSections opening for commercial\nfishing on August 23 at 6:00 a.m.\nwill be the Western, Icy Straits.\nSouthern, West Coast and a por\ntion of Clarence Strait. Day stated\nthat extensive observations during\nthe past week which has been closed\nand latest reports indicate that fish\ning can again be permitted.\nThe sections, which will remain\nclosed next week will be allowed\nopen fishing on the 27th and 28th.\nII there is a change of abundance\nin these sections, they will be allowed\nto continue open. The Pish and\nWildlife Service will announce either\non Saturday or Sunday, August 28\nor 29, whether these sections will\n[remain ap+n r\nDay stated that the critical stream\nj conditions, due to the unusually\nI short water supply in southeastern\nAlaska and the poor showing of\nfish to date may necessitate fur\nther curtailment in any or all dis\ntricts, but future action will depend\nupon the circumstances.\nNo Snap Jadgment\nFar from being snap judgment on\nthe part of a \"vacationing\u201d public\nofficial, the decision on closure was\nreached by Joint agreement of the\nentire staff of the fisheries division\nof the Fish and Wildlife Service,\nClarence J. Rhode said today.\nHe declared, \u201cthe matter of ex\ntensions and closures was considered\nin joint sessions with our agents.\nDuring the last week we have had\nevery agent travelling steadily\nthrough his district checking stream\nescapement and reporting to us\ndtfily on changes.\n\u201cIn addition to that we have\nmade three trips this week by plane\nwith personnel from the regional\noffice checking key spots.\n\u201cWith this information and with\nstatistical information supplied by\nDr. Rich, we sat down in joint ses\nsion, yesterday afternoon, with Se\nton Thompson, chief of branch of\nAlaska fisheries, Oeorge Kelez, su\npervisor of fisheries, Prank Hynes,\nassistant supervisor of tisheries and\nmyself as regional director, with\nMr. Day, director of P It WL ser\nvice, went through records and agreed\non recommendations for opening\nthe season where warranted and re\ntaining closure where insufficient\nescapement was apparent.\nObjections Raised\nReferring to the additional closure,\nW. C. Arnold, Managing Director\nI of the Alaska Salmon Industry,\nInc., said in Ketchikan today that\n\u201cthe fisheries of Alaska are be\nI ing treated as a plaything by va\ncatlontng officials of the Depart\nment of the Interior.\u201d\nHe charged, In a signed statement\nmade to the Ketchikan Daily News,\nthat \"orders have been issued with\nout rhyme or reason by Albert M.\nDay, Director of the Pish and\nWildlife Service,\" now here from\n(Continued on Page Six)\nGLACIER PLANE\nCRACKS UP BUT\nNOUERKMULY\nReports reached here yesterday\nthat a special ski-wheel equipped\nNorseman airplane cracked up last\nTuesday on 8eward Glacier, where\nit was being operated by (he Arctic\nInstitute of North America glacial\nexpedition. The plane was not ser\niously damaged and has returned\nto its base at Yakutat.","height":"26652","width":"20852"}}
